Found one problem similar to a bug. If there is a `#` character in query, everything after that character is removed. For example, if query has form `q=test#123`, then in `$route.query` we get `{q: 'test'}`, but I would like to see there: `{q: 'test%23123'}`, that is so, special character `#` is converted to `%23`).

I tried to solve the problem using `stringifyQuery` option. I created something like:
```
stringifyQuery: function (query) {
    const qs = require('qs')
    const result = qs.stringify(query, {encoder: (str) => str.replace(/#/g, '%23')})

    return result ? (`?${result}`) : ''
}
```
But this unfortunately doesn't work and still drops everything after character `#`. Why does the `vue-router` remove all characters in the query after `#`? Is there a way to undo this?

### What problem does this feature solve?
IMHO, there are several problems with Vuex.

1. Overuse string when using `mapState`, `mapGetters`, `mapActions`
2. Duplicated namespace in components

like this:
_my-component.vue_ (AS-IS version)

```js
export default {
  computed: {
    ...mapState("todos", {
      allItems: ({ items }) => items,
    }),
    ...mapGetters("todos", {
      doneItems: "doneItems",
      activeItems: "activeItems",
    }),
  }
}
```

In this code, `"doneItmes"` is written by string. It will cause bug easily.
And there are duplicated namespace called `"todos"`. It will inhibit maintainabillity.

### What does the proposed API look like?
The way to introduce it is not to suggest a new API, but to use the existing API properly.
We can use `createNamespacedHelpers` API with constants in store directory!

### Example

_@/store/todos/types.js_

```js
export const NAMESPACE = "todos";
```

_@/store/todos/index.js_

```js
import { createNamespacedHelpers } from"vuex";
import { NAMESPACE } from "./types";

// Key point !
const { mapState, mapGetters, mapActions } = createNamespacedHelpers(NAMESPACE);

export { mapState, mapGetters, mapActions };

export default { /* namespaced, state, getters, mutations, actions */ }
```

_@/store/todos/getters.js_

```js
// Key point !
export const DONE_ITEMS = "DONE_ITEMS";
export const ACTIVE_ITEMS = "ACTIVE_ITEMS";

export default {
  [DONE_ITEMS]: state => state.items.filter(todo => todo.isDone),
  [ACTIVE_ITEMS]: state => state.items.filter(todo => !todo.isDone)
};
```

If we do this, we can use customized binding helpers.

_my-component.vue_ (TO-BE version)

```js
import * as todos from '@/store/todos'; // Key point !
import * as getters from '@/store/todos/getters'; // Key point !

export default {
  computed: {
    ...todos.mapState({
      allItems: ({ items }) => items,
    }),
    ...todos.mapGetters([
      getters.DONE_ITEMS,
      getters.ACTIVE_ITEMS,
    ])
  },
}
```

How about this? If you do not mind this, I would like to post it on the official Vuex document.
You can see the all example code in [this repository](https://github.com/JaeYeopHan/vuex-best-practice-lab)

Thanks!

